<PageLayout title="Naming reference" slug="sketches/naming">

<style>
  .ref-block {
    max-width: 900px;
    margin: 0 0 3.5rem 1.5rem;
  }
  .ref-block h2 {
    font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    color: var(--fg);
    margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
  }
  .ref-block .section-note {
    font-size: 0.82rem; color: var(--fg-muted); margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .ref-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 20ch 16ch 1fr;
    gap: 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .ref-grid .rn,
  .ref-grid .rnn,
  .ref-grid .rd {
    font-size: 0.82rem; line-height: 1.55;
    padding: 0.35rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .ref-grid .rn {
    font-family: var(--font-code);
    color: var(--fg);
    padding-right: 1rem;
  }
  .ref-grid .rnn {
    font-family: var(--font-code);
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    padding-right: 1rem;
  }
  .ref-grid .rd {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
  }
  .ref-grid .col-hdr {
    font-size: 0.70rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.07em; text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--fg-muted); opacity: 0.40;
    padding: 0.5rem 0 0.4rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .ref-grid .group-header {
    grid-column: 1 / -1;
    font-size: 0.72rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--fg-muted); opacity: 0.55;
    padding: 0.9rem 0 0.3rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .ref-grid .idx {
    font-family: var(--font-code);
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    opacity: 0.45;
    margin-right: 0.5ch;
  }
  .vocab-group { margin-top: 1.8rem; }
  .vocab-heading {
    font-size: 0.78rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: -0.005em;
    color: var(--fg); margin-bottom: 0.3rem;
  }
  .vocab-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 14ch 1fr;
    gap: 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
  }
  .vocab-grid .vt,
  .vocab-grid .vd {
    font-size: 0.82rem; line-height: 1.55;
    padding: 0.32rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .vocab-grid .vt {
    font-family: var(--font-code);
    color: var(--fg);
    padding-right: 1rem;
  }
  .vocab-grid .vd { color: var(--fg-muted); }
  .vocab-grid .vd em { font-style: italic; color: var(--fg); }
  .vocab-grid-prohibited .vt { color: var(--fg-muted); opacity: 0.55; }
  .vt-bad { text-decoration: line-through; text-decoration-color: currentColor; }

  .policy-list {
    list-style: decimal; padding-left: 1.4rem;
    margin-top: 0.8rem;
  }
  .policy-list li {
    font-size: 0.82rem; line-height: 1.65; color: var(--fg-muted);
    margin-bottom: 0.55rem;
  }
  .policy-list li strong { color: var(--fg); font-weight: 600; }
  .disc {
    font-size: 0.82rem; color: var(--fg-muted);
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
    font-style: italic;
  }
</style>

<div class="monologue">
  Names in use across all demos — shapes, effects, lighting, and stems.
  Flags anything inconsistent.
</div>

<div class="ref-block">
  <h2>Naming policies</h2>
  <p class="section-note">Rules that govern the "new" column. Apply to all categories unless noted.</p>
  <ol class="policy-list">
    <li><strong>Clear.</strong> The name should be self-explanatory without needing to see the thing. Avoid abbreviations and acronyms unless they are established mathematical notation.</li>
    <li><strong>Mathematically true.</strong> The name should reflect what is actually happening in the formula — the underlying surface type, the operation, the parameter that varies. Don't describe the visual impression if a more precise term exists.</li>
    <li><strong>No metaphor or poetic language.</strong> Names describe geometry and motion, not mood or feeling. "Oscillating" not "breathing". "Vertical compression" not "squash" if a more precise term fits.</li>
    <li><strong>Distinct.</strong> No two names in the same category should be confusable or interchangeable. If two names could plausibly describe the same thing, at least one needs revision.</li>
    <li><strong>Consistent patterns within families.</strong> If several items share the same base formula or the same motion type, that relationship must be visible in the name. Don't vary the word for the same concept across entries.</li>
    <li><strong>[Modifier · base] structure for animated surfaces.</strong> Every animated surface name follows exactly <em>[present-participle motion] [mathematical shape noun]</em> — e.g., "Oscillating paraboloid", "Pulsing sphere". Word order is fixed; no exceptions without a documented reason (e.g., the surface is a recognised mathematical proper noun).</li>
    <li><strong>Prefer established mathematical terminology for base shapes.</strong> If the mathematical literature has a name for the surface or structure (paraboloid, hyperboloid, gyroid, lemniscate), use it. Don't substitute an informal synonym ("bowl", "donut", "figure-eight") when a precise term exists.</li>
    <li><strong>No root reuse across different phenomena.</strong> The same root word must not appear in names for conceptually unrelated things. If "ripple" names the static radially-decaying cosine surface, the same root cannot be used to describe animation on a torus or an outward-traveling wave.</li>
  </ol>
</div>

<!-- ── Vocabulary ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<div class="ref-block">
  <h2>Approved vocabulary</h2>
  <p class="section-note">Pick from these lists when composing a new name. Unlisted terms require justification against the policies.</p>

  <div class="vocab-group">
    <h3 class="vocab-heading">Base shape nouns</h3>
    <p class="section-note">The mathematical name of the underlying surface. Used as the final noun in an animated surface name.</p>
    <div class="vocab-grid">
      <span class="vt">paraboloid</span>
      <span class="vd">Quadratic surface opening in one direction; includes elliptic and hyperbolic variants</span>
      <span class="vt">hyperboloid</span>
      <span class="vd">One-sheet ruled quadratic surface; x² + z² − y² = c</span>
      <span class="vt">ellipsoid</span>
      <span class="vd">Triaxially scaled sphere; all quadratic terms positive</span>
      <span class="vt">sphere</span>
      <span class="vd">Zero set of x² + y² + z² = r²</span>
      <span class="vt">torus</span>
      <span class="vd">Surface of revolution of a circle; defined by major and tube radii</span>
      <span class="vt">cone</span>
      <span class="vd">Ruled quadratic surface with a vertex; x² + z² = y²</span>
      <span class="vt">saddle</span>
      <span class="vd">Hyperbolic paraboloid or higher-degree saddle-type surface</span>
      <span class="vt">Gaussian</span>
      <span class="vd">Surface whose equation contains e^(−r²/σ²); bell-curve profile</span>
      <span class="vt">cubic</span>
      <span class="vd">Algebraic surface of degree 3</span>
      <span class="vt">quartic</span>
      <span class="vd">Algebraic surface of degree 4</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="vocab-group">
    <h3 class="vocab-heading">Proper mathematical names</h3>
    <p class="section-note">Recognised names from the literature. Use as-is; do not paraphrase or translate.</p>
    <div class="vocab-grid">
      <span class="vt">gyroid</span>
      <span class="vd">Triply periodic minimal surface; cos(x)sin(y) + cos(y)sin(z) + cos(z)sin(x) = 0</span>
      <span class="vt">Schwartz P</span>
      <span class="vd">Triply periodic minimal surface; cos(2x) + cos(2y) + cos(2z) = c</span>
      <span class="vt">Schoen I-WP</span>
      <span class="vd">Triply periodic surface; cos(2x)cos(2y) + cos(2y)cos(2z) + cos(2z)cos(2x) = c</span>
      <span class="vt">lemniscate</span>
      <span class="vd">Figure-eight curve of revolution; (x²+y²+z²)² = a²(x²−z²)</span>
      <span class="vt">Chmutov T₄</span>
      <span class="vd">Degree-4 surface from Chebyshev polynomials T₄; T₄(x)+T₄(y)+T₄(z) = 0</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="vocab-group">
    <h3 class="vocab-heading">Animation participles</h3>
    <p class="section-note">Present-participle words describing what the time parameter is doing. Used as the leading modifier in an animated surface name.</p>
    <div class="vocab-grid">
      <span class="vt">oscillating</span>
      <span class="vd">A scalar parameter alternates sign periodically; e.g., amplitude goes positive → negative → positive</span>
      <span class="vt">pulsing</span>
      <span class="vd">A magnitude varies periodically while staying positive; e.g., radius or height swells and contracts</span>
      <span class="vt">traveling</span>
      <span class="vd">A spatial feature (wave front, peak) translates through space; the surface moves, not just deforms</span>
      <span class="vt">rotating</span>
      <span class="vd">Angular position increases monotonically; the surface or a feature spins</span>
      <span class="vt">drifting</span>
      <span class="vd">A parameter shifts slowly and continuously without periodicity; no return to origin</span>
      <span class="vt">tilting</span>
      <span class="vd">The orientation angle of the surface varies; a rotation that reverses rather than spins continuously</span>
      <span class="vt">alternating</span>
      <span class="vd">The surface transitions between two discrete configurations; a binary oscillation</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="vocab-group">
    <h3 class="vocab-heading">Spatial qualifiers</h3>
    <p class="section-note">Adjectives or adverbs that specify the geometry of a feature — used when the base noun alone is ambiguous.</p>
    <div class="vocab-grid">
      <span class="vt">radial</span>
      <span class="vd">Depends only on r = √(x²+z²); rotationally symmetric about the vertical axis</span>
      <span class="vt">axial</span>
      <span class="vd">Varies along the primary (vertical) axis; independent of angle</span>
      <span class="vt">angular</span>
      <span class="vd">Depends on azimuthal angle θ; periodic in θ</span>
      <span class="vt">transverse</span>
      <span class="vd">Perpendicular to the primary axis or wave direction</span>
      <span class="vt">sinusoidal</span>
      <span class="vd">Profile follows a sin or cos function; use when the wave shape itself is the defining feature</span>
      <span class="vt">triply periodic</span>
      <span class="vd">Repeating in all three spatial directions; reserved for minimal surfaces and their relatives</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="vocab-group">
    <h3 class="vocab-heading">Prohibited terms</h3>
    <p class="section-note">Words that violate one or more policies, with the preferred alternative.</p>
    <div class="vocab-grid vocab-grid-prohibited">
      <span class="vt vt-bad">swaying</span>
      <span class="vd">Too evocative. Use <em>tilting</em> (if orientation angle varies) or <em>oscillating</em> (if a scalar alternates)</span>
      <span class="vt vt-bad">wavy</span>
      <span class="vd">Describes appearance, not math. Use <em>sinusoidal</em> or <em>oscillating</em> with the axis specified</span>
      <span class="vt vt-bad">bumpy</span>
      <span class="vd">Describes appearance. Specify the perturbation type: <em>perturbed</em> + base, or name the perturbation function</span>
      <span class="vt vt-bad">ripple / rippling</span>
      <span class="vd">Reserved for the static radially-decaying cosine surface (idx 09). Do not reuse for animation or for torus modulation</span>
      <span class="vt vt-bad">wave (standalone)</span>
      <span class="vd">Ambiguous — could mean wave shape, wave motion, or wave equation. Qualify: <em>sinusoidal surface</em>, <em>traveling wave</em>, etc.</span>
      <span class="vt vt-bad">blend</span>
      <span class="vd">Describes an operation, not a surface. Name the result geometrically: what surface does the blend produce?</span>
      <span class="vt vt-bad">twisted</span>
      <span class="vd">Ambiguous between torsion (differential geometry) and casual use. Use <em>rotating</em> if angular position varies monotonically</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

